items.description: A key part of having a reviewable PR is writing commits that tell a story. Present your changes incrementally and logically so reviewers can follow your thought process. Generic commit messages such as "add dependency," "implement file upload feature," and "address PR feedback" don’t tell much of a story and leave reviewers guessing. Why was the dependency added? What were the specific steps in creating the file uploader feature? What feedback is being addressed?

items.title: File over app — Steph Ango
items.description:
File over app is a philosophy: if you want to create digital artifacts that last, they must be files you can control, in formats that are easy to retrieve and read. Use tools that give you this freedom.

File over app is an appeal to tool makers: accept that all software is ephemeral, and give people ownership over their data.

items.title: The Blank Page Revolution - by Steven Johnson
items.description: The most surprising insight, I think, revolves around the significance of the fundamental substrate of all modern notebooks until the digital age: paper. Before reading Allen's book, I had mostly thought about paper in terms of Gutenberg and the printing press democratizing knowledge and information by making it much easier to publish and read printed information in the form of books. But somehow I hadn't fully thought through the more intimate revolution that it enabled—a revolution of self-knowledge and private record-keeping, executed not with a printing press but with a pen.

items.title: Lizzie Wilson Research Page
items.description: My thesis explores the integration of autonomous agents into live coding systems to co-create music with human performers based on affective response, aiming to enhance musical expression and collaboration between humans and machines. By developing prototypes and conducting experiments, the studies conducted demonstrate that autonomous agents can facilitate the emergence of new musical ideas and patterns. The research outlines the creation of an Affective Live Coding Autonomous Agent (ALCAA) and a Markovian Agent for code generation (that leverages Haskell's strictly typed system) named Tidal Fuzz, which together form a hybrid system combining affective and computational models for generating expressive music through code manipulation. The thesis also proposes modifications the Consensual Assessment Technique for live coders, as a means of evaluating the creative outcomes of this collaborative process, acknowledging the subjective nature of creativity and ensuring nuanced evaluation.

items.title: Jimmy Kimmel’s Suspension Is an Escalation in Every Way - The Atlantic
items.description: Of course, mocking the sitting president has long been a cornerstone of pretty much any late-night program throughout the medium’s history. Trump has been the butt of countless jokes over the years. What’s happened to Kimmel is an escalation in every way, a chilling precedent that could have further consequences if it isn’t swiftly undone. How Kimmel himself reacts to the situation will be important—he’s a major celebrity, a multi-time emcee of the Academy Awards who’s been hosting TV shows since the 1990s. There’s a chance network television could become even more reticent to broadcast anything remotely provocative, which in turn could also inspire blowback from their audiences.

items.title: City of Portland will issue land use violation notice for ICE facility, triggering process to determine next steps at the site | Portland.gov
items.description:
Following an investigation, the City of Portland will send a land use violation notice this Thursday for the U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement facility in Southwest Portland – launching a process to determine whether the site’s detention practices comply with the conditions of the site’s land use approval.

Federal government records from a 10-month period show more than two dozen detention policy violations of the facility’s land use conditions of approval with the city, which does not allow detainees to be kept overnight or held for more than 12 hours. The notice also references a second violation related to boarded windows, which is not associated with the land use approval.

items.title: Trump Executive Order Declares NASA Is Now a Spy Agency
items.description:
The Trump administration issued an executive order late last month, quietly declaring that NASA will operate as a national intelligence and security agency going forward.

The order stipulates that the agency will now "have as a primary function intelligence, counterintelligence, investigative, or national security work."

It's a major departure for the agency, which has historically focused on space exploration, as well as space and Earth sciences over its 67-year lifespan.

items.title: Who Will See My Comment? – Climb to the Stars
items.description: Bluesky, Mastodon and Twitter (yeah, and Threads) feel more fragmented. It’s more difficult to follow for lots of people. They are faced with bits and pieces of conversations flying about, and access to the context of those is not frictionless. Part of this, I think, has to do with how publication audience is managed (I’ll definitely have to do a “part 4” about this in my Rebooting the Blogosphere series). And another, of course, is the primacy of non-reciprocal connections on those platforms.

items.title: Where Have All The Bloggers Gone? – Climb to the Stars
items.description: What is happening for me right now is interesting. During my Facebook exile, I reconnected with the social networks that I had been present on in a very passive manner these last years. I also wrote more on my blog (here!), and made an effort to get back into reading other blogs, even though I have never been a really huge blog reader in my past. I installed an RSS reader, and started subscribing, process which is now pretty frictionless. To my surprise, there are lots of blogs! Lots of people still blogging! Lots of people who took up blogging way after the Golden Era of Blogs! I see them show up here and there on Mastodon and Bluesky, and of course, in blog posts.

items.title: You Want Technology With Warts
items.description: Every single wart that annoys us today, used to be a reasonable feature that someone relied on in their production code. Every wart we see today is a testament to the care the maintainers put into backward compatibility. If we choose a technology today, we want one that saves us from future maintenance by keeping our wartful code running – even if we don’t yet know it is wartful. The best indicator of this is whether the technology has warts today.

Peering again at my Obsidian setup. I have daily pages where I juggle to-dos for today, tomorrow, this week, and someday.

Most of the undone to-dos carry over from day to day. The ones in "someday" go to a page where they accumulate forever as aspirations.

I do this all manually, every morning over coffee. I know there are some plugins that can do the carry over, but none of them do what I want.

Tempted to write a node script or something, since I don't want to be locked into Obsidian. 🤔

commits.message:
Add OPML to HTML bookmark converter for Linkding import

This commit adds a new `tohtml` command that converts OPML feeds to Netscape
HTML bookmark files compatible with Linkding's import feature.

## New Features

**OPML to HTML Conversion:**
- `cmd/tohtml.go` - New command to convert OPML files to HTML bookmarks
- Takes OPML file and HTML output file as arguments
- Supports optional tags to apply to all converted bookmarks
- Includes dry-run mode for preview without file creation

**HTML Bookmark Generation:**
- `internal/netscape/exporter.go` - Netscape HTML bookmark format generator
- Produces files compatible with Linkding's import feature
- Includes proper TAGS, PRIVATE, TOREAD, ADD_DATE, LAST_MODIFIED attributes
- Matches Linkding's own export format exactly

**Feed Processing System:**
- `internal/feeds/fetcher.go` - RSS/Atom feed parsing and URL discovery
- `internal/importer/` - Complete import processing pipeline:
  - `types.go` - Data structures and status tracking
  - `discovery.go` - URL discovery from feeds and HTML pages
  - `processor.go` - Concurrent processing with statistics
- Supports multiple feed formats (RSS 2.0, RSS 1.0, Atom)
- Concurrent processing with configurable worker pools

**Enhanced Components:**
- Extended Linkding client with bookmark CRUD operations
- Enhanced OPML parser with feed extraction capabilities
- Updated configuration system with processing options
- Added comprehensive error handling and logging

**Documentation:**
- Development session documentation in `docs/dev-sessions/`
- Updated configuration example with new options

## Usage

```bash
# Convert OPML to HTML bookmarks
linkding-to-opml tohtml feeds.opml bookmarks.html

# Add tags to all bookmarks
linkding-to-opml tohtml --tags "imported,rss" feeds.opml bookmarks.html

# Preview conversion
linkding-to-opml tohtml --dry-run feeds.opml bookmarks.html
```

The generated HTML file can be imported directly through Linkding's
Settings → Import interface.

   - Verifies title and tags match expected values after creation

refactor: eliminate global database connection and magic numbers

This commit makes two major improvements to code quality and maintainability:

## 1. Replace Global Database Connection with Idiomatic Go Pattern

**Problem**: The codebase used a global `var db *sql.DB` which created hidden dependencies,
made testing difficult, and violated dependency injection principles.

**Solution**: Refactored to use a `DB` struct pattern:
- Created `DB` struct wrapping `*sql.DB` connection
- Converted all database functions to methods on `*DB`
- Updated all callers to use `database.New()` constructor pattern

**Files Changed**:
- `internal/database/db.go`: New `DB` struct with `New()` constructor
- `internal/database/operations.go`: All functions converted to methods
- `internal/database/operations_test.go`: Tests updated for new pattern
- `cmd/*.go`: All command files updated to use DB instance
- `internal/fetcher/`: Updated to accept DB parameter
- `internal/renderer/workflow.go`: Updated to use DB instance
- `internal/initialize/initialize.go`: Updated to use DB instance

**Benefits**:
- Eliminates global state and hidden dependencies
- Makes database dependencies explicit in function signatures
- Improves testability and enables proper mocking
- Follows idiomatic Go constructor and method patterns
- Enables concurrent usage of multiple database instances

## 2. Replace Magic Numbers with Named Constants

**Problem**: The codebase had magic numbers (30, 32, 100, 0o755) scattered throughout
with linter exceptions to ignore them.

**Solution**: Created named constants in `internal/config/config.go`:
- `DefaultTimeout = 30 * time.Second`
- `DefaultConcurrency = 32`
- `DefaultMaxItems = 100`
- `DefaultDirPerm = 0o755`

**Files Changed**:
- `internal/config/config.go`: Added exported constants
- `cmd/root.go`: Updated viper defaults to use constants
- `cmd/fetch.go`: Updated flag defaults to use constants
- `internal/database/db.go`: Updated directory creation to use constant
- `internal/renderer/`: Updated directory creation to use constants

## 3. Linter Configuration Improvements

**Removed Exceptions**:
- Removed magic number exceptions from `.golangci.yml` (except regex match count)
- Removed global database connection exception
- Re-enabled complexity linters (`gocognit`, `gocyclo`)
- Re-enabled some gocritic checks (`octalLiteral`, `wrapperFunc`)
- Made `cmd/` exceptions more targeted by file pattern

**Fixed Issues**:
- Added nolint comments for safe SQL formatting cases
- Fixed long line violations with proper function formatting
- Fixed unnamed result parameters in test functions

## Verification

All changes verified with:
- `make format && make lint && make build` - passes without errors
- `go test ./...` - all tests pass, functionality preserved
- No breaking changes to public APIs
